 'PAUL SINGER AND ELLIOTT MANAGEMENT: Billionaire Paul Singer runs Elliott Management, the world\'s most aggressive vulture fund. Elliott has sued governments, seized state assets, and extracted billions from countries unable to defend themselves in court.',
 'ARGENTINA SAGA: When Argentina defaulted in 2001, most creditors accepted restructured debt. Elliott refused, sued, and won a U.S. court order blocking Argentina from paying other creditors. Argentina was shut out of credit markets for years.',
 'SEIZING A WARSHIP: In 2012, at Elliott\'s request, Ghana seized Argentina\'s naval training ship with 300 crew aboard. The crew was held for weeks. The spectacle of a hedge fund seizing a nation\'s warship illustrated vulture capitalism\'s power.',
 'TARGETING POOR COUNTRIES: Vulture funds have sued some of the world\'s poorest nations, Zambia, Congo, Liberia. They buy old debt from these countries\' creditors for nothing, then demand full payment, diverting resources from poverty reduction.',
 'CORPORATE VULTURES: Vulture funds also target distressed companies, buying debt to gain control through bankruptcy, stripping assets, and discarding workers. They profit from destroying rather than building.',
 'LEGAL ARBITRAGE: Vultures exploit differences between jurisdictions. Debt governed by New York law is particularly vulnerable because U.S. courts enforce creditor rights aggressively without considering consequences for debtor nations.',
 'HOLDOUT PROBLEM: When most creditors agree to restructure, vultures refuse and demand full payment. This "holdout "strategy lets them extract more than cooperative creditors, discouraging future restructurings.',
 'LOBBYING AGAINST REFORM: Vulture funds lobby intensively against legislation that would limit their tactics. They\'ve killed bills in Congress that would have required them to accept restructuring terms others accept.',
